NL-Ambush doctrine

1. Shadow the transition

Every sensitive state change gets a shadow record:
	•	prior state
	•	triggering event
	•	actor/context
	•	expected invariant
	•	resulting state

Not just “what happened,” but what it claims to mean.

2. Build the side-angle model

Instead of trusting the direct path, Gatejackal computes an off-axis interpretation:
	•	What else could this transition mean?
	•	What would this look like if spoofed?
	•	What is the nearest hostile equivalent?
	•	What is the least-trust explanation?

This is the flank model.

3. Compare narrative to mechanics

If a system says:
	•	“routine re-auth”
	•	“harmless rewrap”
	•	“normal key rotation”
	•	“standard session renewal”

Gatejackal checks whether the mechanics match the story.

If narrative and mechanics diverge, it triggers scrutiny.

4. Spring only at the hinge

It does not constantly block. It waits for hinge moments:
	•	issuance
	•	delegation
	•	unwrap/decrypt
	•	sign/execute
	•	rotate/recover
	•	privilege escalation
	•	cross-domain translation

This keeps it quiet and high-signal.

