Ambush patterns

Pattern A: Silent Flank

No immediate block. Mark the transition, increase scrutiny on downstream steps, and wait to catch compounding drift.

Use when:
	•	confidence is moderate
	•	false positives are costly
	•	observing the chain yields better evidence

Pattern B: Hinge Snap

Pause the transition exactly at the authority handoff and require secondary proof.

Use when:
	•	privilege increases
	•	irreversible action follows
	•	recovery would be costly

Pattern C: Mirror Corridor

Replay the transition through an alternate interpretation engine and compare outputs.

Use when:
	•	data is syntactically valid
	•	semantics may be corrupted
	•	the system is vulnerable to “looks right” failures

Pattern D: Canary Transition

Inject a harmless, traceable variant into a low-risk branch to see whether the downstream system preserves invariants.

Use when:
	•	you suspect hidden transformation drift
	•	you need mapping without disrupting production

